Skills Development for Economic Empowerment of Youth in Latin America (also called Youth Building the Future project) aims to equip young people with the skills and opportunities to engage in enterprise and employment in targeted regions in Brazil, Colombia and El Salvador. In 3 years, disadvantaged youth will complete life skills training and market-driven technical training or business skills training, at least 75% of which will enter decent employment - either in a job or by establishing/strengthening their own enterprise ensuring future economic security for themselves and their families. This program is supported by Plan’s Regional Office of the Americas (ROA) through technical assistance, evidence gathering support and (academic) research coordination.

By given life-skills training and market-driven (based on a market scan) technical training to young people, they acquire the necessary skills to enter the job market as employees or entrepreneurs. By engaging companies for the development of training content and understanding their needs and expectations regarding future employees, the project facilitates the transit of vulnerable young people to decent jobs. Once these young people have the right skills and are either working or running their own business, they will be able to earn a decent income for themselves and their families.

Learning and reflection are important aspects of the programme. In 2016 a learning agenda will be worked out and this will focus on the continuous assessment of the assumptions underlying the programme’s design and Theories of Change. These will be reviewed critically every year at country, regional and alliance levels, resulting in strategic adjustments where necessary to ensure the maximum effectiveness of the interventions. 

Learning will also be an outcome of the programme’s evaluation agenda. A baseline will be conducted in the first half of 2016 and a mid-term review and final evaluation are scheduled for 2018 and 2020 respectively.

For 2030 Plan envisions a world with universal, sustainable, and equitable access to and use of safe drinking water and sanitation facilities, and improved hygiene behaviours, as well as the elimination of open defecation. All relevant stakeholders (governments, WASH service providers, private sector players, communities) take up their roles in the system of WASH service delivery. Women and men, boys and girls have equal rights and responsibilities in relation to the provision and use of WASH facilities. As a result, in this envisioned world, every person can live a healthy life and develop to his or her full potential. 
The WASH SDG program aims to sustainably improve access to and use of sanitation, improve hygiene behaviors , and improve access to and use of safe drinking water over the coming five years. It is built on three core strategic objectives, namely (1) increasing demand for improved WASH facilities and practices, (2) improving the quality of service provision and by (3) improving governance of the sector. Thereby, Plan’s approach is gender transformative, meaning that significant attention goes to women and ensuring their equal rights and opportunities. The consortium is fully committed to ensuring that services and infrastructure will function well over a decade after construction or rehabilitation. Plan collaborates in country, closely with the local country office, and all their partners within the government, civil society and private sector. Within the country, collaboration as a consortium is an added value.

In the Netherlands the project will provide input for evidence-based lobbying of the Dutch government. It will also link with the Dutch tourism industry and a campaign called ‘Don’t Look Away’. There will also be opportunities for visibility through newspaper and magazine (Vice Versa) articles, radio interviews, presentations during forums and conferences.

EM and teenage pregnancies mutually reinforce one another. Social and gender norms perpetuating EM are deeply embedded in communities and this situation can only be changed if community leaders and most of the people, including boys and men, support the change. Key persons in the communities, including boys and men, will be turned into allies in the process of changing these norms, thereby helping to address the problem of EM and teenage pregnancies. A general lack of information about SRHR and poor quality and access to the relevant services are perpetuating the above-mentioned problems. Adolescent boys and girls are being informed about SRHR and given a voice to claim these rights. Girls are being given more control over their lives. This is being achieved by changing these norms and people’s behaviour, strengthening networks and structures for social mobilisation and embedding these in communities, and by involving the government and the private sector in improving SRHR and services. All these will help to reduce EM and teenage pregnancies.

Due to deficiencies in education quality, and youth’s limited access to business networks, financial services and productive assets, a wide gap remains between the market demand and the provision of well-trained workers. Existing governmental training institutes cannot bridge the skills gap by technical trainings alone; soft skills trainings and post-graduate job insertion has proven to be essential for successful employment of youth.

Based upon pre set selection criteria appropiate students will be selected by Plan Ecuador. Students will then be supported to take the required entry test to enter university. If they pass they will start with their chosen study, which should qualify as labour market relevant as assessed through a market assessement exercise done by Plan. Students will then be mentored, guided and supported while going through their academic year, both in financial terms as in life skills training. Upon graduation students will be supported to the world of work. Upon signing a employee contract at least 50% of the students will start contributing to the revolving fund as agreed beforehand to ensure new students can enter the program. Universities, employers and alumni will be actively involved in the program to strengthen it and ensure sustainability.

During the course of 2016, a learning agenda will be worked out and this will focus on the continuous assessment of the assumptions on which the project’s design and Theories of Change (ToC) have been based. The ToC will be critically reviewed every year at country, regional and alliance levels so that strategic adjustments can be made to ensure the maximum impact of the interventions. 

Learning will also be an outcome of the programme’s evaluation agenda. A baseline will be conducted in the first half of 2016 and a mid-term review and final evaluation are scheduled for 2018 and 2020 respectively.

A community-based cluster sample survey was administered at the household level among young girls and boys aged 15-24 in the intervention area (Mogovolas). The survey included question about child marriage. We obtained a sample size of 1430 using a standard formula- taking into account possible “design effects” because of the clustered sampling- we multiplied the required sample by 1.5 and had a ratio of 75% female respondents and 25% male respondents.  A total of 1482 questionnaires were administered- very slightly above the planned target.
